<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species appears to be related to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the form of the inflorescence and the distribution of the indumentum on the corolla and almost all vegetative parts. It differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the distinctive velvety-grey indumentum and in the shape and size of the sepals which are subequal, ovate, 7-8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6-8 mm. It differs from all related species in the densely pubescent ovary.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Its placement here is unconfirmed.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
